<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911230-0092</DOCNO><DOCID>911230-0092.</DOCID><HL>   Pennzoil to Adopt   Accounting Change   That Will Trim Net</HL><DATE>12/30/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7</SO><CO>   PZL</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)</MS><IN>ACCOUNTING (ACC)OIL-SECONDARY (OIS)PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><NS>ACCOUNTING AND AUDITING NEWS andamp; ISSUES (ACC)EARNINGS PROJECTIONS (ERP)PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   HOUSTON -- Pennzoil Co. said it will adopt a change inaccounting methods that is expected to reduce 1991 net incomeby about $49 million, or $1.21 a share.   In 1990, the oil company earned $93.8 million, or $2.37 ashare, on revenue of $2.37 billion.</LP><TEXT>   Pennzoil said it will adopt the new accounting methodretroactive to Jan. 1, 1991-thus requiring restatement ofquarterly earnings figures released earlier this year. Forthe first nine months, the company has previously reportednet income of $67.3 million, or $1.67 a share, includingprofit from discontinued operations, on revenue of $2.02billion.   The announcement was made after trading ended Friday onthe New York Stock Exchange. Pennzoil's shares fell 12.5cents, closing at $53.625.   The new accounting method, which is being adopted by theFinancial Accounting Standards Board, the chief rule-makingbody for accountants, requires that the costs of providingpost-retirement benefits other than pensions -- such as lifeand medical insurance coverage -- must be accrued over theemployees' active career.   Pennzoil said that although the new accounting methodneedn't be adopted until 1993, it decided to do so &quot;early&quot; to&quot;remove any uncertainty or speculation about&quot; its effect onearnings.   The company added that the expected charge againstearnings &quot;is non-cash, and adhering to the new standard willnot affect Pennzoil's cash flow.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>